  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface to the Songs of Successive Ages and Years
  author: Lee Gyejeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The rise and fall of nations and kingdoms, their order and chaos—these are truly the mirror of emperors and the very subject that scholars ought to study. I humbly reflect that our Sovereign Lord, grieving that scholars are ignorant of history, has exercised his wisdom to commission the compilation of the Instructional Commentary on the Zizhi Tongjian, that it might be transmitted to all ages. Moreover, fearing that beginning students could not survey it comprehensively, His Majesty has brought forth the Songs of Successive Ages and Years by Zeng Xianzi of Luling, commanding the Grand Scholar of the Pavilion of Literary Brilliance to cross-reference and annotate it. Yet since the Yuan Dynasty was lacking, it has been supplemented with poems by Zhang Meihe of Linjiang. And regarding the chronology of our Eastern Land, this too must not be left unknown—so His Majesty commanded the Minister of Personnel to arrange and compile it, with annotations as well, all refined through his own royal scrutiny until it became most complete and clear. Thus, the Chinese histories form the upper volume and our Eastern Kingdom forms the lower, which the Royal Printing Bureau will cast into type and distribute widely. Now I, your humble servant, am commanded to write this preface.

    Having examined this work, though its pages are concise, from the opening of heaven and earth to the present, the measure of dynastic fortune—both long and short—and the joining and separation of state power, from beginning to end, all becomes manifest at a glance. Truly, this is the gateway to the historian's art. Should readers who study this work aspire to comprehend the sacred wisdom of past sages, recite these songs to grasp their essence, consult the full histories for their details, and thereby discern the pivot upon which order and chaos, survival and ruin turn—using these as both encouragement toward virtue and warning against vice—then this book shall not merely benefit those who study. Rather, it shall become an eternal mirror for the countless generations of our Chosŏn to come. Our Sovereign Lord reveres literature and promotes civilization, leaving wisdom for his descendants to flourish—ah, such virtue is supreme.
  footnotes:
    - 'Zizhi Tongjian (資治通鑑): The monumental ''Comprehensive Mirror for Aid in Government,'' a universal history covering thirteen centuries compiled by Sima Guang in the 11th century.'
    - The 'Eastern Land' (東國) refers to Korea itself, here called Chosŏn.
    - Zeng Xianzi of Luling (盧陵曾先之) and Zhang Meihe of Linjiang (臨江張美和) are historical poets whose chronological verses were used as source material.
